"1315","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","about 1310":"about 1310","1382":"1382","about 1330":"about 1330","1260":"1260","about 1340":"about 1340","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hancok","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Hancock  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Hancock","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name   Hann   + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-cok</i>, which was commonly added to personal names (see   Cocke  ).","Dutch: from Middle Dutch <i>hanecoc</i> ‘winkle, periwinkle’ (a type of shellfish), probably a metonymic occupational name for someone who gathered and sold shellfish.","History: Thomas Hancock, the uncle of Declaration of Independence signatory John Hancock (1736/7–93), was among the foremost of 18th-century American businessmen. He was a descendant of Nathaniel Hancock, who was known to have been in Cambridge, MA, as early as 1634. Born in Braintree, MA, John Hancock was president of the Second Continental Congress and the first governor of the state of MA."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":18,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":72,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When William Hancok was born about 1310, in England, his father, Willelmus of Warwickshire Hancoke, was 52 and his mother, Mrs Willemus Hancoke, was 21. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs William Hancock."},"et":{"about 1310–":"umbes 1310–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1315":"1315","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","about 1310":"umbes 1310","1382":"1382","about 1330":"umbes 1330","1260":"1260","about 1340":"umbes 1340","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1310–":"noin 1310–Kuollut","1310–Male":"1310–K